notesStmt.note: Ex-libris of Hildebrand Bradenburg of Biberach: an angel supporting a shield vert, charged with an ox argent
Parchment guards in the middle of every quire

msContents.summary: This manuscript is an early fifteenth-century copy of Jacobus de Voragine's Sermones quadragesimales, which notably contains one of the earliest extant examples of a printed bookplate, that on Hildebrand Bradenburg of Biberach, circa 1480.

supportDesc.extent: vi+240+i; 213 x 147 mm bound to 218 x 156 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Foliated in contemporary ink, near-center top of recto; Letter C is used for 100 and CC for 200 in combination with arabic numerals

p.signatures: Signatures throughout, every twelve leaves beginning folio 13r, lower middle on recto

p.catchwords: Catchwords throughout, every twelve leaves beginning folio 12v, lower right on verso

layoutDesc.layout: Single column thirty-three to thirty-four lines; frame-ruled in pencil, pricking visible; no line ruling; written area; 150 x 101 mm

decoDesc.decoNote: One large initial C with ornamental penwork (fol. 1v); red three-line initials (including some written on their sides) throughout; red touches throughout
[Flyleaf 1 recto]Bookplate of Hildebrand Bradenburg of Biberach, an angel supporting a shield vert, charged with an ox argent

binding.p: Bound in fifteenth-century sheepskin; front cover lined with leaf from an earlier antiphonal; metal bosses and two clasps; past on first flyleaf is the ex-libris of Hildebrand Bradenburg of Biberach, considered the oldest German woodcut bookplate

origin.p: Written at Bopfingen, Württemberg, by the student Johannes Anhang in 1408, finished on the morrow of the feast of the Apostle Thomas (December 22nd); 1408

history.provenance: Hildebrand Bradenburg, gifted to Buxheim in 1480; Juliana Force (sold Parke-Bernet, 17 May 1943, no. 338); gift of Gordan A. Block, Jr., 1956
